### Functional requirements based on the problem statement

1) The system allows enterprises to set policies to allow/deny actions based on user role  
2) The system decisions on user actions  
3) The system provides real time dashboard for enterprise users to monitor security heath  
4) By having a higher subscription plan system provides enterprises auto-remedial action enforced at cell towers  
5) System integrates with real estate developers to register towers  
6) System onboards users and their devices  
7) System auto discovers enterprise devices

### Behavioral expectations can be characterized as below:

1) The system to be high assurance and scalable i-e is highly available, scales to high volume of decisions on user actions and responds with minimal latency  
2) Manages enterprise policies securely with proper access controls and encryption  
3) System enforces industry grade security on its interfaces and data

### Application Layer Services & their responsibilities:

Microservices architecture enables services with single responsibility and data access patterns, it would apply perfectly to use cases defined in the problem. 

Following list defines the services and their responsibilities: 

1) Policy Service \- manages enterprise policies, capture, persistence and makes it available in the cache to be used by the decision service.  
1) DB transactions in PostgreSQL is used to maintain data integrity for critical operations like policy updates, device registration  
2) Policy updates restricted to specific enterprise user roles  
     
2) Decision Service \- enforces the rules i-e approve/deny user actions initiated by the app on the tower equipment. The tower equipment delegates authorization of user action by calling the /action endpoint. This places a message in a distributed queue connected to the decision service.   
   1) This service is scaled up to guarantee low latency turn around by having multiple queue consumers and references cached data to make a quick decision.  
   2) Default Deny should be enforced incase the action is not listed in policy.  
   3) Authentication between tower equipment and RabbitMQ should be done by validating client certificate(x509) 

   

3) ELK Stack \- captures decision logs from stdout using LogStashsâ€™s file input plugin and saves it in Elastic search which indexes data & provides efficient querying and real time monitoring & dashboards using Kibana.  
     
4) API Gateway \- provides api layer endpoints to service requests for   
1) enterprise policy management  
2) decisioning on user actions onto tower equipment  
3) get security health for the enterprise  
4) user onboarding via various sources & auto discovery of user devices  
5) tower onboarding from real estate developers.   
   It also manages security to these endpoints by authenticating and authorizing incoming requests and is responsible for rate limiting, ssl termination.  
     
5) Tower Service \- manages registration of new towers and updates tower configuration cache used by the decision service. Provides batch onboarding mechanisms along with serving the endpoint for onboarding/managing tower config.  
     
6) User Registration Service \- manages onboarding of enterprise users and their devices. Provides batch onboarding mechanisms along with serving the API endpoint for onboarding users and devices. Also services auth-discovery of user devices via the same endpoint  
     
7) Data Validation Service \- Provides schema and data validation for ingestion of bulk data on towers and enterprise users & devices   
     
8) Analytics \- Integrates with ELK querying data from Elastic Search  
1) Collects enterprise security health data from ELK and services get security health endpoint.  
2) Listens to alert events from real time dashboard monitoring for Enterprises with Premium subscription plan and invokes auto remedial action on the tower equipment

### System APIs \[Presentation Layer\]

We could go with REST based apis as it is easy for clients to integrate with them and are proven to be manageable

1) Register Tower(s)

	POST /towers  
	\[{  
		Tower\_id,  
		Carriers: \[list of carriers\]  
	 }\]  
	Auth: 

2) Register Users

	POST /users  
	\[{  
		enterprise\_id,  
		devices: \[list of devices\]  
	 }\]

3) Auto discovery of user device  
   PUT /users/id  
   {  
   	Deviceid, type, os  
   }

4) Register enterprise  
   POST /enterprises  
   {  
   	enterpriseId, name, plan  
   }  
5) Upgrade plan  
   PUT /upgrade  
   {  
   	enterpriseId, newplan  
   }  
6) Policies  
   POST /policies  
   {  
   	enterpriseId, appId, role, allowedActions\[list\], deniedActions\[list\]   
   }  
   PUT /policies/id  
   GET /policies?enterpriseId=enterpriseId  
   Returns \[list of policies\]  
     
7) POST /decision  
   {  
   	towerId, enterpriseId, userId, appId, actionType, timestamp  
   }  
   Response  
   {  
   	actionId, decision, timestamp  
   }  
     
8) GET /monitor/securityhealth  
   Response {enterpriseId, allowedActions, deniedActions, totalActions, score} 

	  
Additionally the system also supports file based ingestion of towers and enterprise users

9) POST /towers/bulk  
   Headers: multipart/form-data

10) POST /users/bulk  
    Headers: multipart/form-data  
    

API Security

- OAuth2 is used for Authentication for requests coming to API Gateway  
- Authorization is enforced by checking the user role from request payload and enterprise subscription

### Persistence Layer:

We would have choices of using relational or NoSQL databases to manage data storage and retrieval in this system. With data having relationships between entities it would make sense to store the data and relationships in a SQL database. Postgres is a proven choice.  
Entities and Schemas

- Tower \[Id, status, location, realEstateDeveloperId\]  
- Carrier \[Id, name, supportedDeviceOS\[list\]\]  
- Enterprise \[Id, name, SubscriptionId\]  
- Subscription \[Id, name, enterpriseId, startDate, endDate\]  
- User \[Id, enterpriseId, role\], status\]  
- DeviceOS \[Id, OS, status\]  
- App \[Id, DeviceOSID,, version\]  
- Action\[Id, enterpriseId, userId, actionType, decision(allow/deny), timestamp, towerId, deviceId, appId)  
- Policy \[Id, enterpriseId, role, appId, allowedActions(JSON), deniedActions(JSON), status, timestamp, activeDate\]

Entity Relationships

- Tower carrier relationship \[towerId, carrierId\]  
- User Devices \[Id. userId. deviceOS\] 

Above entities and their relationships can be modelled in a relational database which allows it to normalize data to store and query efficiently.

### Scalability and Performance Considerations

1) Scaling services Horizontally \- Running microservices as containerized applications using Kubernetes would help scale them based upon expected load and latency requirements.   
2) Cloud Environment \- Deploying microservices onto a managed cloud environment like AWS would help with HA and resilient infrastructure. Along with provisioning and managing other services like Redis and distributed message queue would be much easier and manageable.  
3) For low latency requirement Decision service using a clustered Redis cache will allow quick access to data required (like Enterprise Policies, active user roles, tower configs like carries supported)  
   \- Enterprise policies and tower config can be entirely stored in the cache. Policy and Tower services can be configured to update this as a write thru cache.  
4) Using a distributed queue like RabbitMQ or Kafka to accept user action decision requests to be processed by Decision service will allow it to be scaled and managed effectively under high load.   
5) Storing actions data in ELK will allow us to leverage a proven stack for building analytics and reporting on user actions. It would also be used to initiate alerts acting as a triggering mechanism for higher revenue generating Auto Remedial Service.  
6) PostgreSQL indexes can be used to query user and enterprise 

Infrastructure

1) Databases replication is used for DB failovers and disaster recovery  
2) Metrics for all endpoints is stored in ELK and observability dashboards are build to monitor system performance
